@ThinkingandTinkering This is because you are running at far below the voltage rating of the motor so the mechanical losses in the motor are large compared to the physical shaft torque before stalling. 

In DC motors there is no opposition to current flow in the windings other than the DC resistance of the winding when the motor stalls & also until the motor is rotating. This is why in old time systems there was a rotating handle which clicked series connected resistance until the motor started to turn (see pictures of the driver control of old fashion trolley bus or tram with DC supply via a photograph) In small motors, they are so inefficient that stalling them will simply cause a temperature rise in the winding but this is usually not destructive. In larger motors, stalling will see a large rise in heat because the back EMF is not present & the winding will burn up hence the temperature sensor. In very large motors, with poor protection systems this overheating under a stall condition can be dramatically destructive.

You can run these WM universal motors just fine with lower voltage DC or AC but if you are running them at near their proper rating, you will need speed control involving the sensor so they do not run away with themselves under no physical load.
